INTRODUCTION

An equities analyst is studying the pharmaceutical industry to learn its structure using some basic financial measures. Financial data is gathered on 21 firms in the pharmaceutical industry, including the following variables: market capitalization (billions of dollars), beta, price/earnings ratio, return on equity, return on assets, asset turnover, leverage, estimated revenue growth, net profit margin, median recommendation (across major brokerages), location of firms headquarters, and stock exchange on which the firm is listed. In this assignment, I use k-Means clustering methods to cluster and evaluate these firms.

Conduct WSS (Elbow) Method

Now I use the Elbow method to identify the point where adding more clusters stops meaningfully increasing similarities between the firms in each cluster. Here I see a sharp drop at k=2 and a smaller but still distinct bend at k=3, suggesting that these would be the most meaningful numbers of clusters. This aligns with what I observed in the K-Means plots above.

fviz_nbclust(pharma, FUN = kmeans, method = "wss") # Class slides code produced error in gutter; added FUN

Conduct Average Silhouette Method

As one more angle on choosing the best number of clusters, I run the Silhouette method. This method measures how similar each data point is to its own cluster compared with other clusters. In this Silhouette plot, we see that the firms are most closely related to their respective clusters and farthest from the other clusters when grouped into five clusters. However, two clusters come out nearly the same as five, and three is only slightly lower. Im curious why five clusters emerge above the other numbers of clusters but am encouraged that two and three clusters are once again positive choices.

fviz_nbclust(pharma, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

Profile Plot of Centroids

I want to learn why the firms are clustered the way they are. What commonalities do they have with their cluster neighbors, and what differences do they have with the firms in the other clusters? In Chapter 15, Cluster Analysis, of the Data Mining for Business Analytics textbook, code is given for plotting a visual representation of each clusters centroids. Below, I copy and revise the textbook code to fit my setup. (I needed help formatting the chart to fit the length of my variable names.)

par(mar = c(8, 4, 2, 2))   # enlarge bottom margin

# plot an empty scatter plot
plot(c(0), xaxt = 'n', ylab = "", type = "l", 
     ylim = c(min(k3$centers), max(k3$centers)), xlim = c(0, 9)) # 9 variables

# label x-axes
axis(1, at = 1:9, labels = colnames(pharma), las=2) # las = 2 sets the labels vertically

# plot centroids
for (i in 1:3) {
lines(1:9, k3$centers[i,], lty = i, lwd = 2, col = ifelse(i %in% c(1, 3),
                            "black", "darkgrey"))
  }

# name clusters
text(x = 0.5, y = k3$centers[, 1], labels = paste("Cluster", 1:3))

Analysis

Here I needed to prompt generative AI to behave as an equities Subject Matter Expert (SME). I requested brief definitions of the variables and their significance to an equities analyst. I reference these brief explanations as I inspect the Centroids. In normal circumstances, I may consult further with a SME while forming an analysis, but as the current SME is generative and this is a graded assignment, my relationship here is limited solely to an introductory overview of the terms and their significance. All analysis is my own.

Cluster 1: Target for Acquisition

Cluster 1 is comprised of firms that are low market cap (-0.91), high beta (1.41), overleveraged (1.03), and experiencing low return on assets (ROA) (-1.11). All of these factors could be considered negative to a potential investor. Market cap, according to my SME, represents the total value of the company based on share price times number of shares. This clusters low market cap mean suggests the firms in Cluster 1 are small. Beta measures volatility relative to the market. A beta above one is more volatile than the market. Leverage refers to the ratio of debt to equity or assets. An overleveraged company has too much debt and is at risk of bankruptcy. And ROA refers to the profit generated per dollar of assets. With low ROA, these firms demonstrate deficient operational strategy.

Now, armed with this information from my SME, I put on my analyst hat. While an analyst wouldnt likely advise investment in small, volatile, overleveraged, poorly operated firms, this last factor has me wondering if Cluster 1s firms have been be more competitively positioned were they operated more efficiently. Perhaps the analyst would present this group as an opportunity for acquisition. Having had poor success compared with the market and facing a risk of bankruptcy, the leadership of these respective firms may welcome an exit plan, even if the bid is lower than they would have otherwise valued their companies. And if one of the primary obstacles to these firms success is ineffective operation, a change in leadership could cause a rebound. Acquiring these small firms under the umbrellas of larger, established corporations could also improve performance.

Cluster 2: Explore Further (Possible Risk-Tolerant or Short Term Investment)

For cluster two, I needed to evaluate the factors more closely. There are no sharp outliers. The main features that stand out are a PE_Ratio of 0.87, a ROE of -0.74, and a Net Profit Margin of -0.81. According to my SME, the PE Ratio (Price-to-Earnings Ratio) describes how expensive a stock is relative to its earnings. A high PE Ratio may indicate high growth expectations or overvaluation. While Im not sure exactly which number constitutes a high PE Ratio, my instinct is that this clusters mean of approaching 1 is good but not notably high. The ROE is the Return on Equity, the profit per earned dollar of equity. This shows how efficiently a firm uses shareholder money. Cluster 2s mean is in the negative. And, finally, the Net Profit Margin describes the percent of revenue turned into profit. Cluster 2s mean Net Profit Margin is relatively low, which reveals that they arent currently profitable. However, their relatively low beta of -0.62 suggests stability, and along with it, the potential to rebound.

My main takeaway from observations of Cluster 2 is that the firms contained within it arent performing well but arent in enough distress to likely sell their companies at a loss. It is possible their lower performance may be due to poor market fit rather than poor leadership. There are a lot of other possibilities in these numbers and Id likely explore other methods for evaluation before presenting a cohesive analysis. It is possible these firms would be attractive to a risk-tolerant investor, but I need more information.

Cluster 3: Sound, Long-Term Investment

Unlike Cluster 1, Cluster 3 has a positive market cap (0.67), lower beta (-0.36), lower leverage (-0.33), and a higher return on assets (ROA) (0.83). In short, these companies are stable and profitable. They would likely be sound long-term investments.

Convert and Aggregate

I needed help with this code.

pharma_c   <- read.csv("Pharmaceuticals.csv")
extra_vars <- pharma_c[, 10:12]
extra_vars$cluster <- k3$cluster

# 10 & 11 numeric, 12 categorical
extra_vars$Median_Recommendation <- as.factor(extra_vars$Median_Recommendation)

## Numeric patterns by cluster
num_summary <- aggregate(extra_vars[, 1:2], by = list(cluster = extra_vars$cluster), FUN = mean)

Analysis

Cluster 1

Analysts mostly recommend Hold or Moderate Buy, with no Strong Buy ratings. This matches my earlier conclusion that Cluster 1 contains weaker or riskier firms. The recommendations suggest general caution from analysts.

Cluster 2

Analyst recommendations are distributed across all categories, including one Strong Buy and one Moderate Sell. This aligns with my earlier uncertainty about this cluster. Firms here may have mixed signals or inconsistent performance. This suggests the need for deeper investigation or possibly refining the clustering approach.

Cluster 3

Cluster 3 receives mostly Hold and Moderate Buy recommendations, with some Moderate Sell. This supports my assessment that these firms are relatively stable and strong performers, though I may have recommended them too strongly as dependable long-term investments when their performance is only moderate-to-good.
